Looking back. Ondru & Voiceless Journeys was one of the most incredible art projects I've ever had the chance to be involved with. So I want to share some photos over the week about this project.  It is just as important today as it was years ago and the good work continues.  The photos in the exhibition may look silent but look closer and you'll see an entire story being told through their hands. You'll see the tales of 101 people who have fled their countries due to war or conflict.  It was set up by Desh Balasubramaniam to combat the misleading political rhetoric about ""boat people"" and ""illegals"". It is about art that inspires and challenges as a community at a grassroot level. ""Change can happen when we can see the other persons stories"". It is about given a voice to the voiceless.  If we were really to adopt our @australia anthem we should give credence to the verses ""in history's page
column2: let every stage
column3: advance Australia FAIR"" ""for those who come across our seas
column4: we've boundless plains to share"". It has not been a failing of the people wanting diversity it's a failing of our political elite who are somehow unsure how to live up to the values and promise in our Anthem.  #art #artist #streetphotography #streetart #graphicdesign #graphic #artistsoninstagram #work #volunteer #volunteering #immigration #culture #diversity #community #asylumseekers #australia #voicelessjourneys #ondru #voiceless #voice #listen #speak #catholic #prayers #photo #photography

column1: Diversity is in our bloodlines and love lines.  Interestingly Many if not all the 101 stories had never told their story before.  The project for many was the first time they had felt listened to since arriving in Australia.  This reminds us of the value of listening and often the little emphasis we place on it
column2: the small amounts of space we create for it to flourish and how little we do know about our communities.  Strangely this project opportunity came about for me after a ten day silent retreat
column3: 3 days of silence afterwards and the first time I truly engaged in conversation to speak rather than listen.  This was when I met Desh and we worked tirelessly to make this big project a reality.  The diversity of people that volunteered their time where at some point immigrants upon the land we all share.  #art #artist #streetphotography #streetart #graphicdesign #graphic #artistsoninstagram #work #volunteer #volunteering #immigration #culture #diversity #community #asylumseekers #australia #voicelessjourneys #ondru #voiceless #voice #listen #speak #catholic #prayers #photography #photographer #photooftheday

Modern Slavery can be a defence to drug dealing offences.  Section 45 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015 provides a defence to specific criminal charges where it is shown that they were committed under a compulsion due to slavery or exploitation (for over-18s) or as a direct consequence of slavery or exploitation (for under-18s). The latter test
column2: for children
column3: is less difficult to establish. It is a defence similar to duress.  It can
column4: for example
column5: be used for drugs offences committed as part of a â€˜County Linesâ€™ drugs ring.  What else is Modern Slavery a defence to?  The Modern Slavery defence can be used for any criminal offence not listed in Schedule 4 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015.  It canâ€™t be used for serious crimes like murder
column6: manslaughter
column7: kidnapping
column8: piracy
column9: serious violence
column10: firearms offences
column11: robbery
column12: burglary
column13: arson
column14: criminal damage
column15: most sexual offences
column16: or modern slavery offences themselves. There are other offences to which the defence does not apply.  It can be used as a defence to any other crime. Although it now commonly used for victims of â€˜County Linesâ€™ drugs offences
column17: it also applies to most immigration offences
column18: minor assaults
column19: theft
column20: or conspiracy to do any of these things. Anyone who is trafficked or exploited can potentially benefit from it.  Children may be exploited for a variety of reasons by gangs and used to carry and supply drugs. Children who are particularly vulnerable are often targeted
column21: and they may feel that they can't tell anyone in case they are arrested and punished.  As always

This morning I went back to immigration court for the first time in many months.  From the outside
column2: 201 Varick Street looks like any other office building in New York City. Once you enter
column3: it is a dystopian underworld in the guise of brightly lit rooms where people are
column4: ""just doing their jobs."" When you enter the building
column5: private guards bark orders as you go through security. Stand up against the wall
column6: take off your coat
column7: belt
column8: etc. or youâ€™ll be pulled off the line. No one is treated like this by security in the offices in midtown or Wall Street.  In the last year
column9: the Trump administration has added many more immigration courts in the building. Everything has been squeezed by his deportation machineâ€¦faster
column10: faster
column11: crueler
column12: more inhumane.  In the courtroom the Immigration Judge
column13: clerk
column14: DHS Attorney
column15: and a translator were joking around that they would have any easy day because some of the people who were supposed to have hearings are quarantined for chicken pox.  The women who were having hearings were on VTC
column16: from a detention center in a southern state (video teleconferencing) walk into a sterile room with many chairs. They are all wearing jackets. It must be cold In that room.  Imagine running from danger
column17: making a treacherous journey
column18: then being imprisoned while you ask for asylum.  Imagine seeking justice but you are in detention in one state
column19: the judge is in another state and your attorney (if you are one of the few who has one
column20: none are provided by the court) and translator are calling in from another state.  Imagine being told you have a few weeks until your individual hearing
column21: and you need to pull together all of the paperwork to fight to stay in the USA
column22: and
column23: get it translated into English. This is how you fight for your life while in immigration detention somewhere in the middle of nowhere. #freethemall #abolishICE #immigration

column1: My great-grandmother used to talk about the hacienda she left behind in MÃ©xico. She told stories about what it was like growing up and how scared she was to leave during the Mexican Revolution. This is what I imagine it was like for her. â€¢ â€¢ â€¢ #instawriters #instawriter #instapoetry #instapoet #instapoets #instapoetrycommunity #instawriting #instawriterscommunity #mexico #mexican #latina #mexicana #chicana #chicano #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealth #mentalhealthmatters #chicanos #sanantoniowriters #sanantonio #sanantoniotexas #lgbtq #pride #immigration #immigrantsmakeamericagreat #immigrant #mexicanamerican #brownseries

Thatâ€™s the American flag behind me and the stage is set for a presidential candidate. Last time I was in this very same building in 2015 I was sworn in as a citizen of the United States. I never thought that I will have the privilege to live in this great country and when I arrived here
column2: I felt an immense amount of gratitude just to have my two feet on the ground. I became an American citizen after struggling for many years to obtain my legal status to remain in this country. I will never forget that moment as I was standing here raising my right hand with thousands of immigrants around me repeating the oath of allegiance. I took an oath to support and defend the U.S. Constitution and the laws of the United States. Today
column3: I am standing here in that very same spot making real the promise to support and defend American democracy. I am telling you this story to help us remember who we are as Americans. To help us remember our greatness as a nation of immigrants who make their dreams come true through hard work and determination. I am standing here next to the podium set for a presidential candidate. I didnâ€™t dare to dream this. The United States of America provided me the opportunity to live a life that goes beyond my wildest dreams
column4: to live a life in a way that I never thought was possible. This is my wish for our country today
column5: for all of us to remember who we are at this important moment in history. For all of us to stand together in justice
column6: to make our country more free and more equal. To give everyone access to opportunity
column7: not just some. Today I voted for @berniesanders and I stayed true to the promise I made to my country

Nigeriaâ€™s Civil Aviation Authority (CAA)
column2: has directed airlines operating into the country to comply with the Point of Entry (POE)
column3: policy which mandates intending air travellers to obtain a yellow card before embarking on a journey.  The CAA in a statement the Acting Director General
column4: Capt. A.M. Sidi
column5: the agency said there is an urgent need to fully operationalize the policy due to the ongoing outbreaks of Yellow Fever in the country.  The director general stated that full compliance with the policy will enhance health security in Nigeria and support the global strategy to eliminate Yellow Fever epidemic.  He said: â€œAirlines operating regional and international flights into and out of the country are hereby informed of the Ministerial approval of the Nigeria Points of Entry (POEs) Policy on the prevention and control at cross border transmission of Yellow Fever in Nigeria... How to Bring Spouse or Common-Law Partner in Canadaâœ… â € â—The Spousal Sponsorship Category The Spousal Sponsorship program is a subsection of the Family Class immigration category. Under this program
column2: a Canadian citizen or permanent resident may sponsor a spouse or common-law partner for Canadian permanent residence. â € â•Both the Canadian citizen or permanent resident (also called the 'sponsor') and the foreign national (the 'sponsored person') must be approved by Immigration
column3: Refugees and Citizenship Canada (IRCC) in order for the sponsored person to receive a visa. â € ğŸ‘In order to receive a visa through this immigration program
column4: the sponsor and sponsored person must prove that their relationship qualifies under one of three categories: â € Spouse Common-law Partner Conjugal Partner â € âœ…Outland Sponsorship An Outland application is generally pursued when the sponsored partner is living outside of Canada. However
column5: Outland applicants can still be in Canada and apply through the Outland program
column6: and may be permitted to travel in and out of Canada throughout the application process. Outland applications are processed through the visa office that serves the applicantâ€™s country of origin
column7: or where they have resided legally for at least one year. â € âœ…Inland Sponsorship The other potential option for Spousal/Common-Law Sponsorship is the Inland route. Inland sponsorship is when the couple is together in Canada and the foreign spouse/common-law partner has temporary status in Canada
column8: either as a worker
column9: student
column10: or visitor. The person being sponsored may be eligible for an Open Work Permit
column11: allowing him or her to work for any employer in Canada while the sponsorship application is being processed. â € âœ…After Sponsorship Permanent residence granted under the Spousal Sponsorship program carries certain conditions that must be met: â € The sponsor is financially responsible for the person sponsored for three years after the sponsored person becomes a permanent resident. Individuals who come to Canada as spouses are themselves barred from sponsoring a spouse in turn for five years after receiving Canadian permanent residence. â € Still

column1: In my almost 10 months of living here I've found out one blatantly obvious thing. . . . I  A M  N O T  I R I S H. . I take my tea black
column2: not with milk.  I refuse biscuit
column3: after biscuit
column4: after biscuit.  I never serve the tea at the right time and can't make a tray bake to save my life.  I can't cook with stock cubes.  I prefer other foods to Fish&Chips or Stew.  I don't say the ""ch"" sound instead of the ""j"" sound.  I wear a coat year round
column5: and I will never wear sandals here. I also silently judge anyone who allows their child outside without weather appropriate clothing... I don't talk about the weather properly. I get odd looks when I mention the sun being out for an hour and it's a good day
column6: though the rest of the day is rainy and gray. I get odd looks when I mentioned the rainy
column7: gray day though there was one hour of sun being out.  I don't believe that paracetamol cure is everything.  I don't have cards at the ready for all holidays
column8: celebrations
column9: or accomplishments
column10: but IF I do
column11: I write a full on message on the inside of the card and not just To/From.  I'm honest when I ""should"" be quiet.  I don't fit in
column12: plain and simple as that.  BUT
column13: I'm trying to blend into the culture while still keeping who I am.  Because I've made many a lovely person that thinks differently than me and challenges me where I'm wrong-minded
column14: and I like to think that someday
column15: somewhere on this island
column16: someone will need a coffee loving
column17: bickie-refusing
column18: tea serving (only after the food has had time to settle)
column19: bone-broth cooking
column20: flavour-loving
column21: bundled up
column22: awkward weather conversing
column24: blunt friend
column25: and then I'll be there. column1: â€œMy parents did not tell me until when I was a senior in high school when I was trying to apply for colleges. It was difficult because all my peers were excited about going to a new city
column2: a new state
column3: going to different things that they wanted to do. But I had to keep questioning my parents
column4: ""Why canâ€™t I do this? Why can't I do that?"" When they finally told me the truth
column5: ""You're undocumented so you cannot do anything""
column6: it was very disheartening. Because I felt like I couldnâ€™t do anything. â  â  We deserve citizenship for all because as a human being there is no border on this Earth
column7: and this is our home. The Earth is home
column8: and not just US
column9: not just South America
column10: North America
column11: just anywhere we go is our home and we deserve this right
column12: citizenship for all
column13: because itâ€™s our human rights.â€ â  â  - Christine
column14: one of the 10% of Korean Americans with no pathway to citizenship â  â  Watch our short documentary

column17: and the wildly different reasons people end up in this situation. Link in bio.

column1: This is your chance to make a lasting impact on someoneâ€™s life by helping them overcome language barriersâ¤ï¸ . . One of the most significant obstacles a refugee of immigrant may face is the inability to communicate. As first language English speakers we may take this luxury for granted. . . Imagine being placed in a foreign country without understanding the language. How would you function on a day to day basis - it would be extremely difficult
column2: if not impossible. This further isolates individuals who have already experienced trauma and stunts there ability to become confident integrated members of society. . . At Tapestri we are determined to help close these barriers by providing clients with English tutoring to help immigrants & refugees find there voice in the United States. . . Currently we are looking for 2 Spanish Speaking tutors for 2 different clients. . . A Teenage Girl located in Gainesville & an Adult Man located near Atkins Park. . . Please note this is a volunteer not paid position & transport to the location would need to be provided. â¤ï¸ . . Please share & help us change their lives. . . #refugeeswelcome #galovesimmigrants #galovesrefugees #immigration #immigrantsmakeamericagreat #refugees #refugeestories #teachenglish #englishtutor #languagebarrier #ice #humantrafficking #domesticviolence #philanthropy #nonprofit #livewithoutfear

column1: I have a strict no politics on IG rule because it keeps me sane
column2: but here's the thing: #readingisapoliticalact. If it wasn't
column3: it wouldn't have the same power. So when I say everyone should read #tellmehowitendsanessayinfortyquestions by #valerialuiselli
column4: that statement is both literary and political...because this is beautiful writing but also changed the way I look not so much at immigration but at the causes of the current crisis...why Central American children are fleeing gang violence and what their world really looks like. So thanks much to @eplsdotorg for the invite as part of their 2020 reading challenge to read a book that challenges my point of view. This one did that much more than I ever expected it to.  I have said before that I'm staying out of the #americandirt controversy
column5: choosing instead to focus on adding more #ownvoices Latinx writers to #myreading life. But one thing I don't like about that particular discussion is the myth that the story of immigration in America is one ""no one is telling."" That's just simply untrue and I'm glad this book was on a list of American Dirt alternatives that I found. Valeria Luiselli is telling the story of undocumented children in America
column6: using as her framework the 40 questions she asked them while working as a volunteer translator in immigration court
column7: while waiting for her own green card to be processed. Go read the book. See if it challenges your point of view.  #bookstagram #amreading #librarylove #withmylibrarycard #nonfiction #essays #immigration

column2: I am all smiles here
column3: but theres so much which happened in the two years that led to it that I still cant let go! @storyofstyle post from yesterday regarding how IMGs( foreign medical graduates) are treated differently than local grads stirred up my memories. I might have ended up in Residency and Fellowship easily
column4: thanks to my A* resume
column5: but it doesnt end there. At every point we are expected to be and act like superhumans! I walked in as a pregnant fellow
column6: and it was almost frowned upon. The idea of me going on maternity leave for two months was not entertained by any of the faculty. I was indirectly told how two weeks of maternity leave can sometimes be sufficient. As brutal as nephrology fellowship is
column7: I as a pregnant fellow was made to work extra weekends than the rest
column8: almost working 3week stretches to make up for the maternity leave (this leave was also going to extend my fellowship). I worked 35-36-37 weeks of pregnancy without a day off and I was told I dont have a choice. I had all my research months taken away but one in the following year to make up for the weekdays I was off on maternity leave. And I was told I should be grateful they are accommodating me so well. I walked in an hour late to work one day and I was told â€˜I am not the kind of fellow they want in the programâ€™. This is the brutal truth. They had no mercy. And the unfortunate truth is that the faculty themselves were IMGs but the biases didnt stop. I have cried nights and nights at a stretch. I finished the training with the only fellow who aced her boards. Rest all
column9: all the ones they pampered and spoiled
column10: flunked. I am sorry that they did. But really they needed to hear that. In my IMG world I was a goldmedalist
column11: top scorer
column12: have had my photographs in local newspapers
column13: I was in every way the only kind of fellow they wished they had in their program!  I am glad that I ended up in USA
column14: a country full of opportunities to further my career. But as a physician thats the real truth
column15: we IMGs face a much rigorous training.

column1: It is incredible how many clients we have assisted that have based their immigration plan on what a friend has recommended. When inquiring if the friend is a lawyer
column2: we always get the same answer: â€œNo.â€ It would take dozens of posts to share the horror stories that we have heard from clients who have followed the recommendations of a friend. Although certainly charged with good intentions
column3: these friends are not qualified to guide another in his or her migratory efforts. We always advise our clients to surround themselves with professionals who have proven experience in the area of immigration: lawyers who have been trained to understand and apply the law in the United States and are regulated by the American government to carry out their practices following strict guidelines. Working with professionals is an additional protection for anyone applying for a visa. We work with more than 500 lawyers throughout the country
column4: each with different specializations and profiles. If you are looking to apply for an Investor visa call us today and we will gladly contact you with attorneys that are aligned with your needs and requirements. Remember that obtaining professional support when immigrating not only raises your chances of success
column5: but also identifies possible risks and obstacles that can be easily overcome with the right advice. #immigratetotheusa #entrepreneurship #businessvisa #businessimmigration

column1: Just received an approval on a Removal of Conditions case I did for a lovely young girl who was suffering extreme psychological and physical abuse by her husband. Her husband did so much to ruin her immigration case but after she hired me I got to work on updating her case from a jointly filed one to a waiver based on VAWA. Going through the process I recall how her soul would just bleed as she explained every detail of the abuse. I used to worry about whether she would be able to pull herself together come immigration interview time but I also saw in her heart a resilience that is a quintessential characteristic of the American Dream. I had to ask for details as I needed to present her case. Some days she would say â€œI canâ€™t do this-itâ€™s too painful I think Iâ€™ll just go back to my countryâ€â€”Iâ€™m so humbled by the fact that she trusted me and was so happy to call her today with the news. The best part was that we didnâ€™t even have an interview. Today was about love and justice. I am happy and at peace. #thelovelawyer . . . . #vawa  #americandream #bestfiance #bestfianceever #citizen #deportation #divorce #divorced #dreamscometrue #fiance #fiancevisa #90dayfiance #grateful #gratefulmindset #grateful #greencard #immigrants #immigration #immigrationconsultant #immigrationlawyer #instalawyer #k1visa #removalofconditions #i-751 #lawyerlifestyle #marriage #usa #uscitizen #usvisa

column1: New Jersey Legislature enacts Meganâ€™s Law
column2: which requires community notification when a sex offender is scheduled to be released. Meganâ€™s Law is named for Megan Kanka
column3: a seven-year-old girl from New Jersey who was sexually assaulted and murdered in 1994 by a neighbor who
column4: unknown to the victimâ€™s family
column5: had been previously convicted for sex offenses against children.â € â € Meganâ€™s Laws are state and federal statutes that require convicted sex offenders to register with local police. Sex offenders are required to register with local police and to notify law enforcement authorities whenever they move to a new location. The statutes establish a notification process to provide information about sex offenders to law enforcement agencies and
column6: when appropriate
column7: to the public. The type of notification is based on an evaluation of the risk to the community from a particular offender.

column2: as I've spent most of my life living in Canada. From sledding to skating

column5: I take for granted little joys like getting on a sled and speeding down a hill. My husband on the other hand
column6: moved to Canada as an adult so he didn't experience being a fearless kid going down a hill full speed ahead until he was in his 30s. So when we take Zo sledding

column8: I tested out  the slow motion setting on my camera. I expected to capture some sweet shots of the snow splashing slowly into the air
column9: however what stood out to me most in this particular shot was the look of pure joy in my husband's face as he slid down the hill. â„ğŸ›· #sledding

column2: yâ€™all
column3: I almost didnâ€™t make it to Vancouver because Canada didnâ€™t want to let me in. Why? Because Iâ€™m poor. I wonâ€™t lie
column4: I went in there confident as hell
column5: like this is Canada
column6: Iâ€™ve been here three times and never had any problems. Shoulda known I needed to be on my A game. The immigration officer asked how much cash I had. Then how much money I had access to. Mind you
column7: Iâ€™m not a Canadian citizen
column8: so I had to answer these questions. My brain pictured the $70 in my Savings account and thatâ€™s what I blurted out
column9: even though it was actually $180. Then she made a mark and asked if I had medical insurance. No. Another mark. Then the last straw was when she asked if I had come all the way from Florida for only four days. YES. I SHOULDâ€™VE SAID YES. People do it all the time
column10: ainâ€™t none of her business. But Iâ€™m honest af
column11: and I said Iâ€™d been staying in Seattle for awhile.  She sent me to secondary questioning.  Mind you
column12: Iâ€™m a passenger on a BUS. The ONLY one thatâ€™s been taken aside
column13: and I wait and watch as everyone gets on the bus and has to wait half an hour for me. Because they had a â€œshift change.â€ Right
column14: a shift change that lasted 45 minutes. Anyway
column15: so after a bunch of questions and me basically saying if anything happens
column16: my parents can transfer $ into my account and please let me in
column17: Iâ€™m only going for the New Yearâ€™s holiday
column18: the guy told me that I have no rent or mortgage
column19: I donâ€™t make a living wage and that I had no incentive to return to the US.  HE WASNâ€™T WRONG.  But he is kind and letâ€™s me in. I grab my passport and run to the bus. Shout out to that dope bus driver that waited for me and never made me feel like a burden. And a big middle finger to all immigration. #NoBorders Oh! And the immigration officer that let me in told me he recommends each person have $200 PER DAY when coming to Canada! Say whaaaaat? â€¢ Whatâ€™s your worst immigration story? â€¢ â€¢ â€¢ #Canada #Vancouver #Immigration #Poverty #LivingWage #Capitalism #HeldAtTheBorder #SecondaryQuestioning #CanadaHatesPoorPeople #NYE #Latergram #Travel #SoloTraveler #HostelLife #CrossingTheBorder #GirlsJustWannaHaveFun #ExploreCanada #ImmigrationStories #GallivantsAndRants

Proud to take a stand with the CHED Committee âœ¨âœ¨ . CHEDC Position Statement:  Use of Clinical Notes Against Migrant Children  March 4
column2: 2020  The Cultural Humility
column3: Equity
column4: and Diversity Committee (CHEDC) of the North American Drama Association (NADTA) seeks to bring awareness to an unethical agreement between the Office of Refugee Resettlement (ORR) and ICE to share details about children in their care
column5: including confidential material shared in clinical sessions. The APA noted
column6: â€œThe American Psychological Association expressed shock and outrage that the federal Office of Refugee Resettlement has been sharing confidential psychotherapy notes with U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement to deny asylum to some immigrant youths"" (2020). Not only does this violate the fundamental confidential nature of therapy
column7: but those most egregiously affected are unaccompanied children in shelters
column8: all of whom are required to undergo therapy. The very system that was originally put in place to support minors in dealing with trauma and other vulnerabilities that emerge during the migration process is harming children even further.  These unethical practices of using confidential therapistsâ€™ notes have been used to detain youth
column9: deny asylum
column10: and overturn granted asylum of minors
column11: as reported by the Washington Post and National Public Radio.  This is in direct violation of the NADTA Code of Ethics on ethical practices. Furthermore
column12: the individuals misusing this information are not credentialed clinicians
column13: thus diminishing the paradigm between client and therapist and the confidentiality needed to create a level of safety and trust in psychotherapy.  CHEDC and the NADTA implore the Office of Refugee Resettlement (ORR) and Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) to discontinue these horrific practices immediately.

The Eurasian spoonbill (Platalea leucorodia)
column2: or common spoonbill
column3: is a wading bird of the ibis and spoonbill family Threskiornithidae. The genus name Platalea is from Latin and means ""broad""
column4: referring to the distinctive shape of the bill
column5: and leucorodia is from Ancient Greek leukerodios ""spoonbill""
column6: itself derived from leukos
column7: ""white"" and erodios ""heron"".In England it was traditionally known as the ""shovelard""

column2: and a great reminder of some of the reasons why I do the work that I do. These images represent four important reminders for me today: . 1. I have to be able to look at myself in the mirror every night and know that I am living a worthy life I can be proud of. 2. Speaking out and telling the truth is one of the most difficult
column3: yet necessary
column4: ways of accomplishing this. 3. Many
column5: many people have come before me and many

Victoria University (VU or Vic Uni) is a public research university based in Melbourne
column2: Australia. It is a dual-sector tertiary institution providing courses in both higher education and Technical and Further Education (TAFE). 2020 marked VU's 104th year as an educational institution and its 30th anniversary as a university.  The University has several campuses in Melbourne Central Business District
column3: Melbourne Western Region
column4: and in Sydney
column5: comprising six academic colleges

The government has decided to isolate all illegal Thai workers returning from South Korea
column2: especially those from the North Gyoengsang province and Daegu city
column3: where the number of Covid-19 cases is high.  Prime Minister Prayut Chan-o-cha said the returnees will first be screened in South Korea and those with a fever will not be allowed to board the flight to Thailand.  Upon arrival
column4: returnees from the two South Korean virus hotspots will be immediately quarantined for 14 days at a yet to be decided location.  The prime minister said workers from other areas of South Korea who do not have a fever will be quarantined for 14 days in sites designated by governors in their home province. column1: Genuinely candid photo of me on day 1 in Hawaii
column2: mesmerized by Her sacred land in the green spaces of Queen Liliâ€™oukalani Park in Hilo. â € â € Queen Liliâ€™oukalani (swipe for badass photos) was the sovereign Hawaiian Kingdomâ€™s last reigning royal
column3: overthrown by a faction lead mostly by settlers from the United States in 1893 - lead by an American minister
column4: no less. She was replaced with a new â€œpresidentâ€. President Dole. Yes
column5: those pineapples your eating have a history
column6: too. â € The settlers were
column7: at first
column8: welcomed peacefully. There was an exchange of cultures
column9: a sharing of land
column10: but as the foreign settlers gained a stronghold in agriculture and the economy
column11: they hungered for more power and representation. But The Queen grew weary of the settlers
column12: and rightly so. Economic power was not enough for the settlers and with the support of the US government
column13: they formed a coup and overthrew a sovereign Kingdom and their queen - and Kingdom that was more than generous in welcoming them to their land
column14: and on whose land they had made a fortune. â € â € History books from Hawaii to Europe would have children believe the settlers were victims. But looking around Hawaiâ€™i and seeing the poverty
column15: homelessness
column16: and displacement of indigenous people
column17: it is apparent who the real victims are.â € â € This story followed me everywhere in Hawaii. I knew I was there
column18: free of my passport
column19: free to roam
column20: because ancestors that call themselves American felt in them a hunger for power and a displeasure with peaceful cohabitation on these sacred islands. But I also felt my Indigenous ancestors stirring inside me
column21: like a war of worlds
column22: respecting the sacred land and knowing my country of origin has also disrespected it so. Itâ€™s an inner conflict that peacemakers encounter daily. Because if we want to uphold peace
column23: you are consciously or unconsciously reckoning with the reality of war. â € â € But Queen Liliâ€™oukalani did not go quietly.â € ğŸ‘‡ğŸ‘‡ğŸ‘‡ CONTINUED IN COMMENTS...

One of my earliest memories of my grandmother is of her bouncing my brother and me on her knee singing a nursery rhyme in Korean that roughly translated to â€œJoon Yong and Joon Hyun letâ€™s come out and play together.â€ Those were our Korean names
column2: sandwiched in between our American names â€œChristopherâ€ and â€œAlexanderâ€ on our birth certificates at Eglin Air Force Base
column3: Florida
column4: where we were born. â€” My brother and I were the first ones in our family born in America. At the time
column5: my father was serving in the US Air Force while my mother worked in the backroom of a discount menâ€™s suit shop as a seamstress. As per cultural tradition
column6: Lee Soon Ja
column7: my grandmother
column8: immigrated to America to live with us. â€” Itâ€™s become increasingly difficult for immigrant families to care for their elderly in America
column9: forcing many to abandon their cultural norms and expectations as they turn to the more Western norm of nursing homes. It can also be difficult to afford care tailored to specific immigrant communities
column10: especially those facing language barriers. My grandmother relocated to Southern California when members of my family
column11: who were undocumented
column12: fell terminally ill. She would remain there for the rest of her life
column13: spending the last two years of her life in a hospice for elderly Korean immigrants. â€” This photo is part of the newest chapter of ""America
column14: Again"" â€” a year-long project by the photographers of @VIIPhoto that explores some of the most important issues facing American voters as they head to the polls on November 3rd. â€” Chapter 3: American Dreams includes an essay by author John Edwin Mason
column15: plus six photo stories by VIIâ€™s @EdKashi

Growing Up Undocumented . Queren left her home in Mexico and moved with her mom
column2: dad and brother to the United States at a young age. She didn't realize the full gravity of her status in the US until she was a bit older and started to see some of the consequences. She went through some very dark times
column3: like when her father and brother were detained at the border and deported
column4: and when she was unable to attend her father's funeral in Mexico. . Queren is now a US Citizen
column5: but she's still dealing with the psychological effects of spending so many years living in fear due to her status. Tune in to the Love Beyond Borders Podcast episode 24 to hear Queren tell her powerful story. The Canadian immigration department is working to accommodate visa applicants from China
column2: Iran and South Korea as the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) causes service disruptions and travel restrictions. Nationals of these three countries who have applied for a Canadian visa
column3: but who are unable to comply with certain requirements due to circumstances beyond their control
column4: will be given more time to complete the necessary steps
column5: such as providing their fingerprints and photo. Immigration Refugees and Citizenship Canada (IRCC) expanded the special measures implemented for China
column6: on February 7
column7: to include citizens of Iran and South Korea on February 29. â€œNo application in progress will be closed or refused due to a lack of documentation
column8: â€ the IRCC webpage says. â€œWeâ€™ll automatically give you an extra 90 days to complete these steps. Once youâ€™re able to
column9: complete the steps as soon as possible to avoid delays.â€ The additional 90 days also applies to the biometrics deadline. Though the instruction letter says this step must be completed within 30 days
column10: the IRCC is giving an additional 90 days to those applicants who have been affected by service disruptionsâ€” no new biometrics instruction letter required. IRCC has laid out special instructions for affected permanent resident applicants
column11: work or study permit applicants
column12: and citizenship applicants. In most cases
column13: it is necessary to communicate with IRCC through their online web form. Source: www.cicnews.com #canada_immigration  #canada_visa  #Canada  #immigration  #canada_permanent_residency  #canada_immigration_consultant  #canada_visa  #canada_travel  #canada_coronavirus  #canada_corona_virus

column3: who was wrongly deported nearly 20 years ago

column1: Repost Study: Temporary work visas could deter illegal immigration of Mexican migrants  by: Carnegie Mellon University  Photo Credit: CC0 Public Domain A new study examined how increasing the number of visas available to potential migrants would affect unauthorized immigration from Mexico to the United States. Current U.S. policy bans people who are deported from receiving legal status for a period of time; this policy
column2: called a legal entry ban
column3: is designed to deter unauthorized immigration
column4: but may not work for many Mexican immigrants. The study found that legal entry bans for deported individuals are ineffective at encouraging legal immigration
column5: but increased legalization rates could reduce illegal immigration. The study also found that a temporary work visa program could deter illegal immigration without resulting in large increases in the number of migrants living in the United States. -read the full article here: https://flip.it/cdIQf3 #immigrantstories #immigrationcases #immigration #usa #workvisas

CHAPTER 19 (of 21) By the grace of God and unbeknownst to us
column2: Tiagoâ€™s visa had been issued just prior to the system failure. We received his passport in the mail on July 23
column4: nearly two months after his waiver was approved. By that time we had quit our jobs and moved in with Tiagoâ€™s mother
column5: sister and niece to spend our last weeks in Brazil with them. . In addition to the passport
column6: the consulate sent a large sealed package with strict instructions not to open it. The package had to be turned over to immigration officers upon our arrival in the US. Now all we had to do was make sure the house didnâ€™t burn down with those precious documents inside. That was a legitimate fear of mine. I didn't even want to leave the house for fear that something would happen to that life-changing package. . We spent the last few days savoring every minute with family and friends. There were multiple goodbye parties and lots of tears shed. The goodbye at the airport was heartbreaking. We didnâ€™t know when weâ€™d see our family and friends again. We didnâ€™t know IF weâ€™d see Tiagoâ€™s elderly grandparents alive again. It was all very very surreal and almost like an out of body experience. How could something we had been hoping and praying for for so many years be so painful? . Thatâ€™s all a part of this immigration game. Being in a bi-national marriage is hard. Itâ€™s complicated. But it is so so rewarding. I gained a new perspective on life

column11: and so many dear friends. But now my heart was divided and it always will be. Half of our family and heart lives 6
column12: 000 miles away. Thatâ€™s just part of the deal. . We boarded the plane and sat down in our seats. I remember looking at Tiago in disbelief and saying
column13: â€œWeâ€™re going home.â€ . Hear the full story on the Love Beyond Borders Podcast

HIAS Pennsylvania is excited to announce our new #partnership with the #Philadelphia Furniture Bank!â  â  The @PathtoHousingPA collects furniture donations from the public and in turn
column2: provides furnishings to Philadelphians in need.â  â  We will now be directing our potential furniture donors to the Furniture Bank. The Furniture Bank is able to provide pickup if needed

Experts have calculated that roughly 13 million people were captured and sold as slaves between the 15th and 19th centuries; today
column2: an estimated 40.3 million people â€“ more than three times the figure during the transatlantic slave trade â€“ are living in some form of modern slavery
column3: according to the latest figures published by the UNâ€™s International Labour Organization (ILO) and the Walk Free Foundation. â€” Women and girls comprise 71% of all modern slavery victims. column1: â€˜Adrefâ€™ (Welsh for â€˜homeâ€™) Mixed media painted collage ************************* Every language has a word for â€˜Homeâ€™ Where have you grown roots? Where do you belong? Does every immigrant feel the emotional pull from their place of birth? This painting is my reflection of â€˜Homeâ€™ and what it means to me having lived more than half of my life in Australia
column2: yet still having a constant longing for my Welsh birthplace and family. . ******************** Warning!! Only read on if you like a story! ******************** I spent so much of my teenage life navigating the awkwardness of trying o fit into this new lifeâ€¦.I never quite felt a sense of belonging
column3: that came later with maturity
column4: love and then my children. The funny thing is as Iâ€™ve got older I now feel this pull towards my homeland again. I have two countries that I love
column5: 2 lives with 2 families. . The 3 Starlings (a common bird found in Wales) represent my Australian born children and the Welsh poppies
column6: the many members of my family still living in Wales. I found the word for â€˜homeâ€™ in as many languages as I could for the first layer of the painting. Starlings are also known for mimicking the calls of other birds and mechanical noisesâ€¦.which reminds me of the time I used to come home from school and practice speaking â€˜Australianâ€™ (Welsh was definitely not cool then!) . ...from a distance they look black
column7: but up close they have an almost irridescece sheen with shades of blue
column8: green & purple.  They form a mesmerising phenomenon beyond full scientific comprehension where communication between individual birds allows huge flocks to move in a fluid state of synchronicity.  This is called murmurationâ€¦â€¦my absolute favourite word which I only discovered its meaning at an exhibition at the NGV last year where Cai Guo-Qiangâ€™s enormous flock of 10
column9: 000 porcelain starlings hung from overhead in the gallery
column10: I spent so much time sitting underneath them in awe! Anyone else see this exhibition? Anyhow
column11: thanks for listening to my ramble and â€˜Adrefâ€™ is heading to @Incube8r next week for a #selfportrait exhibition â¤ï¸

Arrived in Jakarta Airport checked at customs
column2: immigration officer asked for what purpose. As usual
column3: I told working for 4 days. He told me if working required working visa.  All this while if I'm working for 3 days no need visa. I started getting fishy. Then he said I need to get a visa which cost 500.000 rupiah. Ok
column4: I pay him
column5: then I asked for receipts he gave me and slip it the passport
column6: then he force me to walk away. After that I realised that not the receipt. Plus the visa date in early date before I arrived. I'm getting pissed with the fucker. Then what's the point. need to attend the office early in Jakarta. I thought Indonesia have changed
column7: unfortunately because of this immigration officer attitude make a bad impression of Indonesian immigration. Now I learn that they still the same. Full of corruption  If one of the reader not agree on this I don't give a damned. Because it involves my expense.  So be careful if you come to Jakarta  #indonesia #viralindonesia #immigration

column2: as well as completely decriminalize border entry and reentry.â € â € It would prevent state and local law enforcement from assisting ICE and CBP in immigration enforcement in any way forcing sanctuary policy down the throats of all Americans. â € â € It would require DHS to fly those criminal aliens who have been removed for committing a crime since 1996 â€” which would result in dangerous criminal aliens being returned AT TAXPAYER EXPENSE back to this country to commit more crimes.â € â € These are just three of the worst policies in The New Way Foward Act

column1: Deputy Prime Minister Gen. Prawit Wongsuwan has confirmed that the government has prepared five facilities to quarantine large number of Thais expected to return from South Korea. column2: these facilities are located at five military bases.  The whereabouts of these places remain undisclosed
column3: due to security reasons.  General Prawit stressed that those returning from South Korea or any other risk countries must strictly observe a 14-day self-quarantine
column4: and must disclose their travel history and health information when inquired by officials.  Failure to do so is considered a violation of the 2015 Communicable Diseases Act

column1: #IAmSuomiToo This is my tenth year in Finland and my time here hasn't been short of challenges. Loneliness and disconnect come inevitably with being an immigrant. When I became a mom
column2: I was completely alone and I struggled hard. I didn't understand the language yet
column3: I didn't have family or friends to support me. I didn't even identify the symptoms of PND. My second challenge with mental health was when I reported years-long sexual harassment at work. When our adopted son came home
column4: I was hit the hardest: secondary trauma and post-adoption depression.  Every time I needed help
column5: it was always out of reach: it was either disinformation (the infamous unknown unknowns)
column6: language barriers
column7: or facing professionals who had no clue what being an immigrant means. I won't sugarcoat it: I'm here today sharing this because I could afford private therapy. I know some other expats in Finland who do not share this privilege and are left alone or at the mercy of volunteer-run community services and Facebook groups.  If you have ever experience or closely witnessed depression
column8: you surely know how hard it is to ask for help. Hitting so many closed doors makes it ten times worse. Having your feelings of loneliness confirmed time and time again
column9: finishes you off. It's time we face the gap in mental health services here in Finland and that we acknowledge that our society is changing and becoming more diverse. Critical services like mental health care must evolve as well. I am part of this country like anyone else: #IAmSuomiToo.  If you want to support this cause and make sure everyone access mental support
column10: please sign the petition linked in my profile.  #iamsuomitoo #finland #lifeinfinland #expatlife #expatinfinland #masennus #mielenterveys #mentalhealth #inclusion #immigrants #immigration #suomi #expats #multiculturalfamily

column2: I met Mario and his single father during a break in their travels. On their make-shift cardboard bed
column3: they managed to find a moment of stillness in their journey of 1
column4: 616 miles. Mario informed me that they were separated from his mother several miles back. His parents couldnâ€™t afford to have his family travel together. His mother decided to stay behind because she believed his father was better suited to protect him on the road. Mario also told me that a lot of other kids were very sick because of the climate. He thinks his father is protecting him from being like them. Thankfully
column5: Mario looked ready to go--after a quick nap. As they rested at the Mexican border with Guatemala
column6: there was a lot of tension in the air. Due to pressures from Donald Trump
column7: the city of Tapachula was unsure if it should allow migrants passage through his borders. The pair was very stressed if they could make it through Mexico. Their desperation was so strong
column8: but turning back was not an option. #rest #fineartphotography_bw #migrantcaravan #immigration #mÃ©xico #usa #centralamerica #refugees

!!!Important Announcement!!! Please read & stop panicking!!! Visas: CEAC Case Status Change  Last Updated: March 5
column2: 2020 On March 3
column4: the Department of State made an update to the Consular Electronic Application Center (CEAC) website
column5: our online portal for visa applicants. A visa applicant whose case previously displayed as being in â€œAdministrative Processingâ€ on his or her case status page now displays as being â€œrefused.â€ There has been no change in such applicantsâ€™ actual cases. This is an administrative change to more accurately communicate case status to applicants.  Visa applicants whose case status on CEAC had previously displayed as â€œAdministrative Processingâ€ had been refused under section 221(g) of the U.S. Immigration and Nationality Act (INA). Although some refusals under INA section 221(g) can be overturned
column6: the change in the CEAC correctly reflects that the applicantâ€™s visa application has been refused.  That status may change if the applicant can demonstrate to a consular officer he or she is eligible for a visa or if information comes to the attention of the consular officer from other sources that resolve any outstanding issues relating to the applicantâ€™s eligibility for the visa.  The applicant should refer to the instructions the consular officer gave at the end of the visa interview and to travel.state.gov/visas for more information about his or her case. column1: It is a common misconception to think that if you have been deported from the US
column2: you could never apply for permanent residence again. However
column3: after deportation
column4: when the person has completed 10 years without entering the US (which is the stipulated time when someone is deported)
column5: they may be eligible to re-enter the country legally .  Important Concepts Deportation is the formal â€œexpulsionâ€ of a foreigner from the US when it has been determined that he/she can be removed for violating immigration laws. After April 1
column7: foreigners in the US may be subject to removal based on deportation laws; this function
column8: now called removal
column9: is handled by the US Immigration and Customs Enforcement Service (ICE) and deportation is regularly ordered by an immigration judge .  Permanent Residence When we talk about â€œPermanent Resident
column10: â€ â€œResident Alien with Permitâ€ or â€œGreen Card Holder
column11: â€ it means that the person is a Legal Permanent Resident (LPR). These statuses define any person in the US
column12: who is not a citizen
column13: and who resides in the country under a legally recognized residence status .  After I have been deported

column3: the United States Border Patrol established a roadblock on U.S. Highway 1
column4: just south of Florida City. The only access point by land from the Florida Keys to the mainland was closed
column5: and people leaving the Keys were treated as though they were exiting a foreign country. The U.S. Border Patrol claimed that the roadblock was established to stop â€œillegalâ€ immigrants from entering the mainland United States from the Florida Keys. Every car leaving the Keys was checked thoroughly by the Border Patrol
column6: including unlikely hiding places such as glove compartments and under seats. The seventeen mile traffic jams that accompanied the roadblock had an immediate negative impact on tourism in the Florida Keys. Reservations were cancelled
column7: hotels stood empty
column8: and local attractions had no customers. Community leaders from Key West filed an injunction against the U.S. Border Patrol roadblock in Federal Court in Miami. The court ruled that the roadblock could continue. As Key West Mayor Dennis Wardlow left the courthouse
column9: he was greeted by press from around the world. When asked what would happen next
column10: the mayor said
column11: â€œTomorrow at noon
column12: the Florida Keys will secede from the Union!â€ The press
column13: and Federal agents
column14: flooded Key West the next day. As promised
column15: at noon on April 23
column17: Mayor Wardlow read a Proclamation of Secession
column18: declaring that Key West would now be a sovereign nation known as the Conch Republic."" KNOW YOUR HISTORY; if you're going to fly a flag
column19: you should probably know what it represents. also

column21: enacting policy to weaken our national park & public lands protections and denying climate change rather than dealing with it. if you live in / love the keys

Want to know what modern slavery - forced labor looks like in Ohio? â€” In June of 2018 Kendra Ross won a $8 million settlement after being trafficked in plain sight. After being forced to work without pay in Kansas City
column2: Atlanta
column3: Newark
column4: and New York City she ended up in Dayton. There she was forced to wait tables at a restaurant (Food for Life Supreme). She was limited access to the outside world
column5: only allowed to speak to the people in the house she was living in and forced to undergo an unlawful marriage. â€” Despite the threats of murder if she tried to escape she managed to leave with the help of relatives and non-profit organizations. â€” We talk about â€œif you see something
column6: say somethingâ€ constantly
column7: for Ross it was if she was at the restaurant willingly. That is why we need to notice the signs. Are there children working that should be in school? Are the staff able to converse with the customers outside of â€œbusiness.â€ How often are they able to take breaks? Are they able to keep their tips? Ultimately
column8: if you have a feeling call the National Human Trafficking Hotline. column2: Across the Horn of Africa
column3: war
column4: abuse and poverty make millions miserable and drive thousands to attempt to flee. With land borders cut off or closed
column5: and surrounded by conflict on all sides
column6: one of the only means of escape is by sea.  The book â€œA Million Shillingsâ€ follows the journey of desperate emigrants
column7: or tahrib
column8: to their embarkation points with smugglers on the coast of Somalia
column9: on a perilous voyage across the Gulf of Aden
column10: and onward in the search for a better life. The cost is just $50
column11: or one million Somali shillings. â€‹ â€‹Find out more about this project with the link in bio. â€‹ â€‹Caption: Somalia
column12: Bosasso
column13: January 2007
column14: Watching over a group of refugees at one of his network's safe houses hidden deep in Bossaso town's back streets
column15: thirty-four year old 'big fish' smuggler Omar lights a cigarette. â€‹ â€‹Working at sea since he was a teenager
column16: Omar spent years helping local fishermen to hunt down sharks for their fins but illegal commercial fishing put an end to the business. He involved himself instead in the arms trade
column17: ferrying weapons to and from Yemen. War in Somalia provided him with new financial rewards however when Bossaso became the country's hub in human trafficking
column18: as more and more people began to flee the brutal fighting while warlords tore the country apart. The financial rewards for him are the main draw. He now makes a minimum of $5000 per month ferrying migrants and refugees across the Gulf of Aden to Yemen; far in excess of the average income of just $100 a month in Somalia .Omar may be a big fish in Bossaso but he is just part of a bigger countrywide chain. His unnamed network has offices in Mogadishu
column19: Belet Weyne and Galkayo in southern Somalia
column20: and Burao on the Ethiopian border. ""These tahrib pay $20 to one of our offices before making their own way here- a receipt then guides them to me when they get here and I charge $50 to get them to Yemen but then the boat owners and agents take commission
column21: and of course we have to pay off the authorities"".

column1: THE UNDOCUMENTED AMERICANS; Karla Cornejo Villavicencio: thank you @oneworldbooks and @netgalley for an advanced copy! This book needs to be on your reading list for 2020! Go pre-order
column2: itâ€™s out on 3/24/2020! I chose this book for a reading prompt â€œA book by a woman that inspires meâ€. And Karla has done that and then some! I can tell you itâ€™s definitely in my top 10 for the year! Karla was the first undocumented immigrant to graduate from Harvard
column3: and she weaves together these stories in such a way that makes you feel deeply connected to each individual. She has done so much
column4: seen so much
column5: and continues to be a voice and an advocate for those that need her. Iâ€™m truly inspired. You can tell she knows what sheâ€™s talking about
column6: because she has lived it! The work she has put into this creative non-fiction is astounding and one of the most heartfelt reflections of undocumented Americans that I have ever read. She takes the real life world that isnâ€™t reflected in big media stories and truly shows how beautiful the Latinx community is. Her steadfast and determined personality shines through in her writing as she gives us a look inside the daily lives of undocumented Americans from around the U.S. all of which are facing hardships and grappling with the huge questions of love
column7: duty
column8: family
column9: and survival. Sheâ€™s also very sarcastic and funny at times
column10: which shows how often those that face the hardest things in life are still some of the most self-sufficient
column11: caring people themselves. . I felt my own family reflected in the pages as I read. My dad is not comfortable talking about growing up as a child of an immigrant. I can see the confusion and pain in his eyes when he talks about it. He always goes on the say that we were all born here and that we donâ€™t have to worry about that. Itâ€™s heartbreaking
column12: and I can feel that fear passed down through the generations. I see now how assimilation has effected our family over the years from when I was a child. My dad was taught to just blend in as best as possible
column13: and not be seen. He taught me the same - keep your nose down and work hard. Passing the torch of what â€œgoodâ€ immigrants are supposed look like. (Continued in comments)

column2: 1968 - In the largest high school student strike
column3: an estimated 15
column4: 000 Latino (mostly Chicano) students walked out of classes in protest of unequal conditions in Los Angeles Unified School District high schools. They walked out despite school administrators barring doors. They walked out despite helmeted police officers wielding night sticks. At the time
column5: there were two reported cases of student beatings during the March 6 walkout at Roosevelt. Despite news outlets like CBS
column6: NBC
column7: and the L.A. Times being at the walkouts
column8: the police violence toward the students was not covered in the media. column7: or tahrib

column12: Al-Baida
column13: May 2007
column14: Illuminated by torchlight
column15: the dead body of a man is discovered in shallow water at Al-Baida Beach. Bloody marks around his face reveal that he had sustained a heavy beating prior to being thrown into the sea. One of a group of three hundred and sixty five migrants and refugees to have arrived in Yemen that night on two smugglers? boats launched from Somalia
column16: survivors witnessed passengers being pummelled with rifle butts and knives as they protested at being dropped far from land. In the dark sea
column17: many succumbed to the water
column18: disorientated and unable to swim. By morning
column19: a total of thirty-four bodies were found at Al-Baida; either drowned or killed at the hands of the smugglers.

column1: EXPRESS ENTRY  As an online program
column2: Express Entry was introduced by the federal government in 2015 to enable qualifying skilled workers to apply for permanent residence. The program consists of 3 categories: Canadian Experience Class
column3: Federal Skilled Worker
column4: and Federal Skilled Trades Class.  As a point-based system
column5: the program first ranks then selects candidates with the most points based on factors such as age
column6: level of education
column7: work history
column8: language skills
column9: and job offer in Canada. Applicants with higher ranks will receive an Invitation to Apply (ITA) for permanent residency through Express Entry.  If you need help applying for permanent residency via Express Entry

column1: Russian President Vladimir Putin and Turkish President  Erdogan have reached agreements that could end fighting in northwestern Syria. 	A cease-fire will come into force in the Idlib province at midnight. 	Putin said he hoped the deal would end civilian suffering and help contain a humanitarian crisis. 	The deal envisages setting up a 12 kilometer (seven-mile) security corridor along the M4 highway south of the city of Idlib. The corridor will be jointly patrolled by Russian and Turkish troops. 	Putin said he and Erdogan reached agreement on a joint document during talks in Moscow that lasted for more than six hours. 	While he agreed to the cease-fire

column3: but what is so beautiful about art is in they way humans create to express a feeling through different mediums to unify
column4: connect and share with the world. Art makes a big impact when itâ€™s expressed in a way people can understand
column5: not usually through logic but through the heart and feeling. Art can breakdown our barriers of judgment and bring people together in a symbolic way. When humans experiences a piece of art that they connected to
column6: itâ€™s something they never forget. To me the Monarch installation represents humanity and nature living and existing together as one. Butterflyâ€™s are the most favorited insect for the delicately
column7: beauty
column8: color and metamorphosis. Mexico has the largest colony of Monarchs that is absolutely breathtaking
column9: and very critical to preserve. Monarchs travel north of Mexico at certain seasons
column10: as they make the journey up so do humans in search of a better life. Symbolically monarchs have no borders where as humans do. We should all be able to go
column11: live and exist as we want
column12: as nature allows. What I loved about this project too was seeing the way being surrounded by the monarchs made people having their portrait taken feel. To me I witnessed grace
column13: joy
column14: contentment and excitement all of which the monarch butterfly emulates as they move through the world. I hope we can all continue to carry and feel these things in our lives
column15: and consciously be aware and care about our environment and all the creatures living in it

column1: â€œThe trick to doing it is asking Americans to pity us while reassuring them with a myth as old as the countryâ€™s justifications for slavery - that is

column7: The Undocumented Americans. . . How many posts or comments defending American Dirt have I read saying stuff like: I know I wouldnâ€™t survive what Lydia and Luca went throughâ€ or â€œmigrants are amazing because I know I wouldnâ€™t had made it here through the desertâ€. Unfortunately
column8: too many. Latinxs we arenâ€™t superheroes
column9: we ainâ€™t made of kryptonite or have been stung by a radioactive bee. We are human like everyone else. To think that people of color are more resilient to pain or should be admired because of their ability to SURVIVE in a racist system
column10: is ... well pretty racist. This book is amazing. The best Iâ€™ve read in such a long long time. It â€˜ll make you laugh
column11: cry and get angry. It doesnâ€™t make US Latinx humans
column12: it makes the reader human through a roller coaster of emotions. Karla did not take the people she interviewed for the book out of a â€œfaceless brown massâ€ and gave them voices; she takes our wireless headphones out of ears
column13: and make us listen to our surroundings. We donâ€™t live in a bubble. Undocumented migrants and their loved ones have always been there but we have chosen to listen to something else. Something cheerier that wonâ€™t ask us to feel or take responsibility for our privilege. She said no more. And I thank her for that from the bottom of my heart. . . column1: Today
column2: BHSECQâ€™s Dream Team went to Bard College to lead a workshop on the importance of social justice and civic engagement. We discussed many social and political issues involving the prejudice against immigrants and the roles they play in the different environments we surround ourselves with. We also introduced students from different Bard institutions to our Immigrant Voices Magazine and how we use it as an outlet to share the immigrant experience. The audience created their own monarch butterflies as a symbol of the journey of migration. - #immigration #dreamteam #nyc #newyork #immigrantvoices #immigrantstories

column1: Dreamer Prayers  The Eldridge Street Synagogue is one of the few remenants of the huge Jewish community that used to occupy what is now New York City's Chinatown. It was built during a period of mass immigration (1880-1924) as more than 2.5 million Jewish immigrants arrived to the US
column2: with the vast majority settling in the Lower East Side. It was the first great house of worship built on the LES by Eastern European Jews.  The facade combines Gothic
column3: Moorish and Romanesque elements. The design uses a numbering pattern that may be drawn from Kabbalah. The local press marveled at the imposing 70-foot-high vaulted ceiling
column4: magnificent stained-glass rose windows
column5: elaborate brass fixtures and hand-stenciled imitation marble walls.  The building began toÂ decline followingÂ the introduction of the 1924 Immigrant Quota LawsÂ and worshipping in the main hall eventually stopped in the 1940s and it fell into disrepair. Restoration efforts from 1996-2007 saved the building and the iconic 2010 monumental stained glass window by artist Kiki Smith and architect Deborah Gans resulted in the dazzling space as it is today.  #newyork #lowereastside #manhattan #nyc #synagogue #jewish #heritage #migration #immigration #worship #religion #gothic #moor #romanesque #architecture #vaultedceiling

These same types of commonsense public health measures were in use whenÂ The Intercept investigatedÂ border crossingsÂ between the Democratic Republic of Congo and Rwanda during an Ebola outbreak last year. But screening efforts at major crossing points were being undermined by harsh restrictions imposed by the Rwandan military at neighborhood and informalÂ foot crossings. Just finished reading Chip Shop in Poznan by Ben Aitkin. A Christmas present
column2: probably not a book I would have picked up
column3: but a great read I thoroughly enjoyed.  It is a personal account of Ben's year as a migrant from Portsmouth to Poland. The book is entirely written as entries in a diary - all in the present tense - which I found unusual
column4: but it really draws you in
column5: make you feel you are in Poland with him. His style of writing is incredible
column6: so observant of small details
column7: so quick to pick up on the absurd things in life we take for granted and so witty and humourous.  It is also a skilful commentary on British politics
column8: on migration
column9: on European history
column10: on media representation of issues - very thoroughly researched - and all woven into his personal - often hilarious -  experiences whilst working and living in Poland and talking to the people he met.  You will enjoy reading it
column11: and it will leave you thinking about the issues after you put the book down.  #poznan #chipshop #billaitken #poland #immigration #europe #goodreads #witty

column1: As many as half a million Central American migrants annually hop aboard freight trains colloquially known as â€˜La Bestiaâ€™ (The Beast) on their journey through Mexico to the United States. They sit atop and grip the sides of La Bestiaâ€™s screeching steel railcars
column2: facing accidental amputation or death if they slip.  At each stage of the journey
column3: migrants are subject to extortion
column4: theft
column5: rape
column6: and even murder if they fail to pay â€œprotectionâ€ fees established by gangs and cartels that control the route north. Gang members have been known to push migrants off moving trains if theyâ€™re unable to pay. Sexual violence
column7: particularly against migrant women
column8: is also commonplace.  Organized crime groups arenâ€™t the only ones profiting off migrants aboard La Bestia. Some train conductors also take part in the chain of extortion by demanding bribes
column9: particularly of women and families with young children. Since most migrants riding La Bestia are traveling without proper documents
column10: and because Mexican authorities often participate in the abuse
column11: most crimes that happen along the tracks go unreported. The majority of the migrants taking the train sleep on the train tracks. #labestia #fineartphoto #fineartphotography #documentaryphotographer #immigration #migrants #asylumseekers #centralamerica #mexico #usa #border #train

Usung Tema Imigrasi Sahabat
column2: Kanim Malang Sapa Masyarakat Kota Batu  MALANG - Sebagai wujud peningkatan kualitas pelayanan publik terhadap masyarakat
column3: Kantor Imigrasi Kelas I TPI Malang menyelenggarakan Pameran Keimigrasian dan Layanan Paspor Simpatik di Kota Batu. Bertemakan Imigrasi ""Sahabat"" yang merupakan singkatan dari Santun dan Hangat Menyapa Batu
column4: kegiatan tersebut terselenggara berkat sinergisitas antara Kantor Imigrasi Kelas I TPI Malang dengan Lippo Plaza Batu. Kegiatan yang direncanakan selama 2 hari dan berkahir pada hari Minggu (08/03) tersebut berlokasi di dalam Lippo Plaza Batu (Batos). Dalam kegiatan ini
column5: masyarakat Kota Batu dan sekitar dapat melakukan pengurusan paspor baru maupun penggantian.  Sejumlah 50 pemohon rencananya akan dilayani pada setiap harinya guna memenuhi antusias masyarakat Kota Batu dan sekitar dalam proses pengajuan dan pembuatan paspor. Tidak hanya itu
column6: Kanim Malang juga melayani pemberian informasi keimigrasian
column7: panduan tata cara pendaftaran antrian paspor online. Bekerjasama dengan pihak Lippo Plaza Batu
column8: pemohon keimigrasian juga mendapatkan free coffee dan suvenir cantik.  Pada hari pertama(07/03) ini
column9: terlihat sekali animo masyarakat yang sangat tinggi akan kegiatan ini
column10: terlihat beberapa pemohon paspor yang sudah berkumpul didepan pintu masuk sebelum Lippo Plaza Batu dibuka. Tidak lupa
column11: beberapa pemohon menginginkan kegiatan yang sangat baik ini dapat digelar secara kontinyu sehingga masyarakat Kota Batu tidak perlu jauh ke Kota Malang dalam proses pengajuan paspor dan juga pemohon dapat menikmati suasana yang nyaman apabila pelayanan publik dapat digelar di sebuah pusat perbelanjaan atau Mal. (Humas Kanim Malang) . . @kemenkumhamri @ditjen_imigrasi @kemenkumhamjatim #kemenkumham #ditjenimigrasi #jatimpastihebat #imigrasi #immigration #imigrasimalang #malang #malangkipa #indonesia #keimigrasian #salamsejiwa #SDMUnggulImigrasiPastiMaju #BerkasLengkapProsesCepat #TertibAdministrasiPelayananSimpati

column1: NEWS IN DETAIL : Ghojadanga of West Bengal and Agartala of Tripura designated as immigration check posts  On March 6
column3: Ghojadanga of West Bengal and Agartala of Tripura were designated as land immigration check posts. They are located in Indo-Bangladesh border.  Highlights  The Government of India has designated Agartala and Ghojadanga to check all classes of passengers entering to and exiting from India. The immigration posts will check travel documents of the passengers.  Legislation  The check posts were authorized under Passport rules

column1: IT'S NOT YOU
column2: ITS ME. Friendors! (Friend-vendors) I truly am interested in you as a person and what your creative business has to offer. I love being a cheerleader and supportive to others. I just don't have much free time for ""coffee chats"" at this stage of my life. I have had to turn down many offers recently to meet for coffee and face to face chats
column3: and I feel so rude turning them down. But
column4: time is valuable.  Time is valuable. And right now
column5: I don't have much free time. I have some really good friends in my life
column6: but I haven't alloted much time for them. I feel guilty about this. I value those realationships
column7: those ones that truly know me
column8: have walked a road with me
column9: supported me. I'm sorry I'm not a good friend right now
column10: I'm sorry I'm not investing much time with you.  The Canadian in me wants to apologize and say sorry. But actually
column11: I take responsibility for my priorities. My children and family are my number one priority. My paying clients are a priority. Once I get my husband back
column12: and I'm not solo-parenting
column13: I will be there for you
column14: I will reconnect and walk with you.  Time is valuable. It's my responsibility to manage the time I do have well! ""Stewardship"" is my 2020 goal and that means using my time I have wisley. . . Photo: @shaelinefaithphotography

column2: letâ€™s remind ourselves that Christian heritage is being increasingly destroyed in some parts of Europe

column2: by Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie  Dear Chimamanda
column3: I am blown away by this book. I wasnâ€™t really sure what to expect when my friend lent it to me because it didnâ€™t really seem to be about anything but life. But then I underestimated the gripping nature of the experiences of Ifemelu in America.  One of the most fascinating things about this novel was the idea that when immigrants come to America
column4: they become black. It opened my eyes to the cultural nuances that England and The States have that arenâ€™t common in native countries. The experience of being black is portrayed in such a powerful way
column5: using blog posts to differentiate from non-American blacks and African Americans. I learned so much about the culture of both Nigeria and America that I hadnâ€™t expected to.  I loved the raw nature of your writing. You donâ€™t use hyperbole or embellishment
column6: you just report the story as it happens. This is beautiful literature and could easily become a classic.  I enjoyed the romantic nature of the novel as well. It wasnâ€™t the straight forward love interest I expected and so it was nice to see something different.  This was a fantastic novel
column7: filled with insights and emotion. Iâ€™d strongly recommend it for any American audience especially
column8: as thereâ€™s much in there you might not understand about your own culture
column9: but as a British reader
column10: just think everyone now should read it.  Thank you for producing such a coherent

During the late-1920s
column2: the KKK arrived in Canada but found limited success for the most part. In Saskatchewan though
column3: they found a hotbed of people ready for their blend of anti-immigrant
column4: anti-Catholic and anti-Quebec rhetoric.  With memberships surging past 40
column6: the Klu Klux Klan was able to intimidate residents
column7: committed acts of arson and would help bring down the Liberal government that had governed for 24 years at the time
column8: bringing in the Conservatives that many accused of being close to the Klan in the province.  From telling residents that Quebec was trying to make Saskatchewan a second French-speaking province
column9: to rallying against the immigration of what they saw as â€œundesirableâ€ Europeans
column10: the impact of the Klan in Saskatchewan would be felt for decades after the organization left the province in the 1930s.  Hope you enjoy my latest episode of the podcast. Current reading.  I just started this book and I am already wide-eyed at how our world is shaped by policy.  Page 10 states that in 1869
column2: ""the officers' role
column3: (onboard a ship headed for the United States)
column4: ""was to guard the Chinese women bound for sex slavery 'until the load of human freight was delivered at the destination fixed by the companies.'"" This
column5: for me
column6: raises two questions: ""Who financed this? Which companies?"" and
column7: ""To serve and protect whom?"" #amreading #history #immigration

column1: Photo by @alixandrafazzinanoor / @noorimages | From the #NOORShop
column2: Across the Horn of Africa
column3: war
column4: abuse and poverty make millions miserable and drive thousands to attempt to flee. With land borders cut off or closed
column5: and surrounded by conflict on all sides
column6: one of the only means of escape is by sea.  The book â€œA Million Shillingsâ€ follows the journey of desperate emigrants
column7: or tahrib
column8: to their embarkation points with smugglers on the coast of Somalia
column9: on a perilous voyage across the Gulf of Aden
column10: and onward in the search for a better life. The cost is just $50
column11: or one million Somali shillings. â€‹ â€‹Find out more about this project with the link in bio. â€‹ â€‹Caption: Djibouti
column12: March 2008
column13: Â Nine year old Kali Abduhi Omar stares at her reflection in the screen of a broken television set as she sits in a make-shift room in one of Djiboutiville?s illicit doss houses.Following a mortar strike on her family?s home in central Mogadishu
column14: Kali and her younger brother have just arrived in Djibouti after spending weeks on the road in a bid to escape Somalia. Their exhausted mother curled up in the corner of the room is sick and scarred from bullet wounds she sustained in the attack. Four other Somali women and their children share the cramped space with Kali as they wait to hear news from a female contact about the smugglers who will help them continue their journey in their bid for asylum in Yemen.
