The Migrant : I met Mr Prakash near a busy intersection while coming back from work today. Mr Prakash hails from a small village in Rajasthan just like me. Most of the hawkers at signals in Hyderabad are from my home state Rajasthan who migrate to metros as Rajasthan doesn't have many employment opportunities. My story is similar to Mr Prakash in some ways yet different in so many others. Story of humanity is the story of migration. We have always been on the move from villages to towns
column2: from town to cities and from one continent to another. The motives have varied. Sometimes it's for survival
column3: sometimes escaping the persecution and sometimes to seek prosperity.Â  Be that is it may
column4: this continuous migration has created the world as we know. However
column5: despite this continuous migration
column6: there has always existed the concept of aliens and foreigners. Earlier inhabitants have termed the recent migrants foreigners. Earlier immigrants have sought to restrict the entry of recent immigrants and in many cases
column7: created deplorable living conditions for them forgetting struggles of their own forefathers. However
column8: they must not forget that sooner or later
column9: the world they inhabit will change again and they might have to migrate soon and they might be subjected to the same treatment. Perhaps we must keep in the mind the old proverb â€œDo unto others as you would have them do unto you.â€ Else sooner or later our indifference or our complicity will cost us dearly. - AD  #migrants #immigration #immigrants #nrc #history  @gurmeharrr @anishgawande @xyzacruzbacani @hannahreyesmorales @monaris_

column2: Refugees and Citizenship Canada (IRCC)
column3: you may apply for a work permit within Canada while being on visitorâ€™s visa under these circumstances: - A valid study or work permit is held by your spouse or parents. - You want to apply for a permit for a different type of employment while possessing a permit for your current work. - You possess a temporary resident permit with a validity longer than half a year. - As an applicant for permanent resident status while within Canada
column4: you pass stages in the process that allow you to apply for a work permit. #immigration #canada #canada_immigration #mana #manaimmigration #visitorvisa #visitor_visa #visitorvisacanada #visitor_visa_canada

column1: Please see the details on our new Business Manager Visa Plan.  YOUR PASSPORT TO BRITISH CITIZENSHIP *. No interviews on applications * No interviews on extensions * No Bank Information required * No innovation requirements *.No monitoring between visa applications  THE OPPORTUNITY  We have corporate applicants based in the Isle of Man which is part of the British Isles. They are looking to develop and expand their businesses by recruiting the right business managers from overseas who have the right skills and the right business acumen and connections to match their ambitions.  THE QUALIFYING CRITERIA  We will need to consult with you to see if you meet the standards demanded but broadly if you would have met the requirements of the now abolished U.K. Tier I Entrepreneur Visa in all major respects then you stand an excellent chance of satisfying the tests we need to apply.  THE ISLE OF MAN  You must be willing to establish yourself on the island as a resident but the arrangements envisage that you will be obliged to spend periods of time outside the island. The exact amount of time will depend on the nature of the opportunity in each case . We set out here Information about the Isle of Man which makes it a sought after place to live and work.  THE KEY BENEFITS  We have identified them above and the visa process is not complicated. To realise these exceptional advantages you must of course keep to the terms of your visa and your contract with the Company you are working with. We deliver solutions to global clients immigration needs. Find out how we can help you visatier.co.uk/iom #iom #isleofman #immigration #visa #businessvisa

column1: While I am so grateful to have had the opportunity to volunteer this week at the border and assist asylum seekers
column2: I leave with a broken heart for the trauma I witnessed. The walls
column3: both physical and legal
column4: that our country has erected to separate ourselves from the plight of humanity is disgraceful. And to top it off
column5: our â€œlegalâ€ system inflicts yet more trauma on those fleeing violence
column6: rape
column7: torture
column8: and political persecution. The stories we heard are tragic

column1: Christian originally from Honduras is an unaccompanied minor rides on the infamous El tren de la muerte (""The Death Train"") refers to a network of Mexican freight trains that are utilized by U.S.-bound migrants to more quickly traverse the length of Mexico
column2: also known as La Bestia (""The Beast"") and El tren de los desconocidos (""The train of the unknowns""). Although these trains (which transport products and materials including corn
column3: cement
column4: and minerals) are regarded as a free form of travel that allows migrants to avoid Mexico's numerous immigration checkpoints and 48 detention centers
column5: the risks are high and many riders are left with life-altering injuries that limit their capacity to work. Christian is well aware of the risk of the train but his desperation and dream to arrive to the USA is greater than his fear. #fineartphotography_bw #fineartphoto #documentaryphotographer #fineartphotography #bwphotography  #immigration #migrants #labestia #trendelamuerte #trainofdeath #photography #socialjustice #art #artforsocialchange

column1: Our client Jamaga from Jamaica ğŸ‡¯ğŸ‡² came to us to remove the conditions on her and her two childrenâ€™s green card. Typically
column2: to remove conditions on a temporary green card based on marriage you must file with your spouse or ask for a waiver based on other reasons.  Jamaga couldnâ€™t file with her spouse and had to file on her own under one of the other reasons. When you file without a spouse
column3: you usually have to go to an interview and answer questions before a decision is made but in our case
column4: not only did Jamaga and her kids get Approved for her permanent resident (10 year green card) in six months but neither of them had to attend any interview. Join us in congratulating our client for this next phase of her life.  This is a result of filing a properly prepared petition. As immigration continues to evolve on a weekly basis

column1: Immigration appeal  When an applicant request to enter Canada refuses or the officer doesnâ€™t allow the applicant to enter Canada
column2: the applicant can request appeal to convince the officer to enter Canada. There is a variety of situations when an applicant can request appeal: -	You have sponsored a family member whose application for permanent residence was refused
column3: you may want to appeal that decision to the Immigration Appeal Division (IAD) in order to explain why the visa application should be accepted. This is known as a sponsorship appeal. -	If you have received a removal order
column4: you may be able to appeal your removal to the Immigration Appeal Division (IAD) in order to explain why you should be able to stay in Canada. This is known as a removal order appeal. -	Generally
column5: the Immigration and Refugee Protection Act (IRPA) requires permanent residents to be physically present in Canada for at least 730 days out of every five years. If you are a permanent resident who is outside Canada and a visa officer (also outside Canada) finds that you did not meet your residency obligation
column6: you may lose your permanent resident status. You can appeal the decision to the Immigration Appeal Division (IAD) in order to explain why you should keep your permanent resident status. This is known as a residency obligation appeal. -	If the Immigration Division decides that you are not inadmissible and can remain in Canada
column7: the Minister of Public Safety can appeal to the Immigration Appeal Division (IAD) within 30 days of the decision. This is known as a Ministerâ€™s appeal. You can participate in the appeal in order to explain why you should be able to stay in Canada. #canadavisa #canadaimmigration #immigration #immigrate #immigration_consultant #canada #Sepimmigration

column1: ğŸ’«Book ReviewğŸ’« for #MigrationMarch â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€” Girl in Translation by Jean Kwok is a story of a poor Hongkonese immigrant girl trying to survive in America. It is basically a Rags to Riches narrative told in Young Adult genre. There is a number of familiar tropes here: an outsider girl with a superpower
column2: an unknown and hostile land that she tries to navigate
column3: a dead parent
column4: useless adults
column5: and a love triangle are those that I could spot. No fairies
column6: thankfully. The presence of tropes doesnâ€™t mean the story is bad. I liked the descriptions of immigrant life
column7: toil at a factory (the author reportedly drew from her own childhood experience)
column8: life in Chinatown. I appreciated the authorâ€™s use of language
column9: threads of Mandarin
column10: and the protagonistâ€™s trouble with English
column11: as well as changes in writing that corresponded to changes in the characterâ€™s language ability. Although the romance part felt strained to me
column12: I loved the questioning of the meaning of Riches in the end. I was very glad at the resolution and the idea that even when you have superpowers

column4: abuse and poverty make millions miserable and drive thousands to attempt to flee. With land borders cut off or closed

column6: one of the only means of escape is by sea.  The book â€œA Million Shillingsâ€ follows the journey of desperate emigrants
column7: or tahrib
column8: to their embarkation points with smugglers on the coast of Somalia
column9: on a perilous voyage across the Gulf of Aden
column10: and onward in the search for a better life. The cost is just $50
column11: or one million Somali shillings. â€‹ â€‹Find out more about this project with the link in bio. â€‹ â€‹Caption: Yemen
column12: Bir-Ali
column13: May 2007
column14: Having arrived in the middle of the night following a fifty-seven hour long voyage from Somalia
column15: dawn breaks over a group of Ethiopian migrants and refugees at a sandy beach near Bir Ali on Yemen's southern coast. A pair of tiny fishing boats sailing close together brought a total of two hundred and fifty-three tahrib within sight of land but coming under fire from Yemeni soldiers
column16: quickly turned around and headed back out into deep waters. Returning the following night for a second attempt at offloading their human cargo
column17: smugglers demanded extra money from passengers if they wanted to be dropped close to shore. Despite being unable to swim
column18: most were thrown overboard two kilometres out at sea as they protested. At least thirty passengers are estimated to have drowned. Only twenty-three of the bodies were ever found.

column1: My parents sacrificed and uprooted their comfortable lives in Panama and brought me and my siblings to the USA. but ultimately I chose to become a citizen because I knew that I could dream bigger and work hard to achieve them in this country. Taking the oath here in a couple of months will validate my feelings about how great this country is. It made me feel proud to be a citizen of a country that is a beacon of democracy
column2: freedom
column3: and justice. I remember thinking about how all the other people were just like us. How we were all leaving loved ones behind to come to this amazing county

column5: and liberty to be who you want to be and we must continue to fight for those values. South Korea has agreed to help monitor Thai workers before they return to Thailand to ensure they are free of the coronavirus.  Government spokeswoman Narumon Pinyosinwat said Prime Minister Prayut Chan-o-cha made the request so Thai workers seeking to return home would be safe and treated if they are infected.  According to the spokeswoman
column2: Thai workers will stay in South Korea for 14 days before their return so that Korean officials can monitor their conditions.  The monitoring in South Korea is among the three measures the Thai government has requested from the country.  Another measure is for South Korea to screen all air passengers before their departure to Thailand. The other is for Korean immigration police to gather the profiles of Thai workers bound for Thailand. column1: Pacific Blvd. was once a a vibrant cultural and a shopping destination for many immigrants in the surrounding Latino communities. This arcade was a hub for young kids and families. It was opened for many years but has since closed down. This was very interesting because this is telling a story of the dynamics of the area. The offspring of these Latino communities are from a different generation and like different  things compared to their parents.-LV photocredits:googlemaps #urpcontext  #huntingtonpark #immigration #intergration #newculture

Marco Mendicino laid out his vision for Canadaâ€™s immigration system today in Toronto. Mendicino opened his speech by stating that Canadaâ€™s future depends on immigration. As an aging country with a low birth rate
column2: Canadians are living longer and not having enough children to maintain the size of its population.  This places greater pressure on Canadaâ€™s economy and fiscal standing. This is due to fewer workers being relied upon to fund rising government expenses
column3: such as health care
column4: which will become more expensive to deliver as the share of elderly Canadians continues to rise.  Mendicino said a major part of the solution is to welcome immigrants. Today
column5: some 80 per cent of Canadaâ€™s population growth will come from immigration
column6: and estimates suggest this will reach 100 per cent by the 2030s.  This is why Canada will welcome over one million immigrants over the next three years
column7: said Mendicino
column8: as he noted that he will formally table Canadaâ€™s 2020-2022 Immigration Levels Plan in March.  Express Entry will remain the flagship program for welcoming immigrants to Canada and has been successful since launching in January 2015. Mendicino noted that 95 per cent of Express Entry arrivals have jobs and some 80 per cent are working in their fields.  In addition
column9: programs such as the Global Talent Stream and Atlantic Immigration Pilot have been key to supporting Canadaâ€™s economy. Nonetheless
column10: there remains a need to promote the benefits of economic immigration to smaller communities across the country. This explains why the federal government launched the Rural and Northern Immigration Pilot in 2019.  The Municipal Nominee Program (MNP) is another initiative that the federal government will pursue to help economic growth across Canada.  Welcoming immigrants will help to grow the labour market

column1: We want you to know our Local Nesters because they are the glue that holds The Nest together. More than anyone
column2: they understand the language
column3: culture and experiences of the children in The Nest. We rely on them to help us navigate through all of it.  Today on International Women's Day we introduce you to 17-year-old Jane (name changed). Her story can't be
column4: shouldn't be
column5: written. But her dreams are something we would love to share with you. ""Nowadays
column6: all I dream of is feeling safe
column7: to be able to be financially stable
column8: to not worry as much
column9: to go back to school. I dream of traveling like we used to. Getting to know different places. I dare even imagine one day going to culinary school and becoming a chef. My dream is to create new ice cream flavors. I remember once
column10: when I was young
column11: I made my mother some ice cream. It was supposed to be strawberry and cream flavored. My mother laughed at my attempt but hugged me and told me thatâ€™s how it all begins
column12: by trying. I would love to be able to create a Mexican Hot Chocolate flavored ice cream."" We hope that one day Jane gets to live out her dream. To all the women who volunteer in The Nests from Mexico to Greece to Africa - we are so grateful for you all.  To learn more about The Nest and sign up to volunteer alongside women like Jane visit www.thinkwithus.org  @ohfcommunitycenter

On this #womensday Iâ€™m uploading my new photo series: â€˜Visa Wifeâ€™. I have never published self portraits and Iâ€™m extremely nervous while doing this! â€˜Visa Wifeâ€™ is a photographic project about moving to a country where one legally cannot work. I am giving viewers an entrance to the personal space of my house and my existence
column2: and by extension
column3: into the lives of the other several thousand â€˜Visa Wivesâ€™. What are they really doing if they have nowhere to go on a Monday morning? Getting bored is an understatement. The struggle of making a to-do list is real. My story
column4: as revealed in my photographs
column5: is at once extremely personal and unavoidably common in the USA. I feel that many people will be able to identify with the ideas that I am exploring through this series of photographs
column6: and will be able to appreciate the inherent complexity and exaggeration in the images. . THIS IS HOW TO OBTAIN UK RESIDENCY THROUGH TURKISH BUSINESS VISA  Turkeyâ€™s Citizenship by Investment program has a unique attraction that many other Golden Visa program do not offer. The Ankara Agreement between #Turkey and the #EEC permits Turkish nationals to apply for a Turkish Businessperson Visa
column2: which allows them to reside in the UK.  Applicants must either start a new business in the #UK or help to run an existing UK business. This Visa is initially granted for 12 months with an option to later extend for a further three years. It is also possible to apply for indefinite leave to remain in the UK after one has resided there for five years. The initial application takes just 12 weeks.  Applicants must firstly apply for their Turkish passport making a minimum real estate investment of $250
column3: 000 + costs. The #citizenship application can be processed within three months. Following approval
column4: applicants can then apply for the Turkish Businessperson Visa in the UK. Based on these average processing times
column5: it will take approximately six months to gain both #Turkish Citizenship and the UK business Visa
column6: making the entire process fast and cost-effective compared with other direct UK immigration routes. Due to the Brexit transition period
column7: we urge applicants considering this route to act promptly. Applications submitted before 31st December 2020 will still be processed. column1: Visapaq COVID 19/CORONAVIRUS Updates.  VISAPAQ is aware of the impact of Covid-19 across the globe
column2: and we are sending our best wishes to all our clients and their families
column3: wherever they are. We want to take a moment to let you know what is happening in regards to our services and immigration at this time: *There is currently no change to USCIS operation (that means still slower processing times so do not put off starting your first application or renewal!) Please proceed as you have been instructed
column4: or reach out for assistance if needed *VISAPAQ is currently still offering in person sessions in NYC (when available) and of course our full coaching program for those outside of NYC
column5: or for those who at this time would feel more comfortable working from home. *When booking a session in person in NYC you must let us know if you have traveled from or through any of the countries currently listed on the CDC website in the previous 14 days. We will still happily work with you
column6: but it will be by Skype only. *VISAPAQ's standard policy is to ask clients to postpone should they feel unwell
column7: at this time postponing or switching to Skype if you feel sick in any way will now be MANDATORY. We are waiving all rebook fees for March to assist with this. DO NOT ATTEND AN IN PERSON SESSION IF YOU FEEL UNWELL *If you have booked an in person session
column8: please go to reception to confirm the room allocation AND USE THE HAND SANITIZER AVAILABLE ON THE COUNTER. Visapaq staff will ensure the meeting room facilities have been wiped down.  The VISAPAQ team is monitoring the situation closely and may issue future directives to ensure our clients' and staff's wellbeing
column9: should the need arise. All of this is part of VISAPAQ's unwavering commitment to our clients success on their visa journey. If you have any other questions or need to book a session do not hesitate to reach out.  Sincerely
column10: The Visapaq Team  #coronavirus #covid19 #immigration #safety #skype #uscis #artist #visa #

A year ago
column2: on March 7th
column3: I said goodbye to my beloved friend and grandmother
column4: Elvira. Her funeral was held at the same church on Southern Boulevard in the Bronx
column5: where she married my grandfather. I was full of grief. My tears came well after the funeral.  Elvira was the embodiment of love
column6: perseverance
column7: compassion
column8: and humor. She and my grandfather worked tirelessly to give my mom
column9: my brother
column10: and I
column11: a chance at a better life than what they could afford for themselves. As a Mexican immigrant living in the pre â€œwhite-flightâ€ Bronx
column12: she was persecuted through sexism and racism by those who saw her as an infiltrator. She endured sickness
column13: loss
column14: and grief. And yet
column15: she always found the strength to support her family through humor and uncompromising love. At great cost to her personal safety
column16: she was a fierce advocate for civil and elder rights. Iâ€™m lucky to have known her and Iâ€™m blessed to call her a part of my family. Iâ€™ve had a lot of pain in my life recently
column17: and it gets easy to count the losses. But Iâ€™m trying to reframe the way I remember her. Rather than a loss
column18: I view her as a cherished
column19: impossible-to-describe
column20: life-long moment
column21: filled with lessons of right from wrong
column22: hard work
column24: and love. And while moments may be fleeting
column25: our memories have a way of making them eternal. Te amo mucho

Recently
column2: I was able to travel to Angel Island in San Francisco Bay with my Mandarin class to learn about Chinese immigration into the US. In collaboration with @brendon_mh I wrote music to a short trailer that he filmed. This is a topic that is both very triggering and very important. Please take the time to read some of the history below.  Some quick facts about Angel Island: â€¢ Angel island was an immigration and deportation station that controlled and regulated foreign entry into the U.S. from 1910-1940. â€¢ Angel Island processed a total of one million immigrants
column4: 000 of those were Chinese. â€¢ While European immigrants were able to pass through Angel Island with relative ease
column5: Chinese and Japanese immigrants were detained for long periods of time before being allowed into the country. â€¢ While on Angel Island
column6: Asian immigrants were subject to exhaustive interrogations that violated their rights.  Why this is relevant: Immigration has been at the forefront of modern day politics. As we think about this problem today
column7: it is important to look back and understand the history of immigration in our own community. Immigration is not just something that is happening in bordering states or a small corner of the US
column8: but is very relevant in the past and present history of our community. Angel Island is just one example of how our country has failed to uphold the rights and freedoms we claim to offer. It is also important to remember that all types of minorities have been in some way mistreated and marginalized in our community. Reminding ourselves of mistakes we have made in the past can help ensure that we do not repeat history in the future.  Please share this with your friends and family. Letâ€™s spread the word about a lesser known part of this countryâ€™s history. . . . . . #angelisland #musicvideo #history #historyfacts #immigration #immigrantsmakeamericagreat #chineseamerican #musicproduction #musicproducer #albion #music  #ableton #identity

I'm a gamer. I've been one most of my life since before some of you were even born. I started out on a Compact Mac with games like Banzai and Crystal Quest. But I eventually made my way through Apeiron and X-Wing to the land of consoles where I played games like Asteroids and eventually Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of Time (still my favorite game to this day)
column2: and now I'm on my Xbox (and eventually PlayStation)
column3: a definite console gamer (yes yes I know pcmasterrace and all that ğŸ˜‚). And none of the consoles that exist now or in the decades since the original Atari and Magnavox
column4: could have been possible without the genius and drive of a man named Jerry Lawson.  He pioneered the concept of a modular gaming system. Cartridges and discs? Yeah he built the concept and put it into play (harhar). Everyone kept saying that a microprocessor not only COULDN'T be out in a game system
column5: it SHOULDN'T be in one because it ""doesn't belong there"". I can imagine that Jerry Lewis took those kinds of comments personally
column6: because as a black man in an industry almost entirely dominated by white men
column7: he knew better than most what it means to be told that they ""don't belong there"". He was tapped to head up an electronics program designed to develop gaming consoles
column8: and he used that to create the Channel F
column9: a modular gaming system
column10: where you could play multiple games on a single system. Because in that era of gaming
column11: consoles came preloaded and could not have games swapped out. Without his contribution
column12: the gaming industry might look very different today.  To Jerry Lawson
column13: I say thank you

column1: Diploma Leading to Bachelor Studies â€“ Benefits  After completion of an educational course
column2: a student gets a chance to receive two types of recognition
column3: either a diploma or a degree or Diploma Leading to Bachelor Studies. These both are educational but are entirely different from each other and interchangeable. Letâ€™s discuss first what these both are:  Diploma VS Degree Lasting for a period of 1 to 2 years
column4: a diploma is a short term course. You can achieve a diploma in your desired course from any leading institute. It is a certificate that is awarded to the students after the successful completion of the course they joined. A certificate awarded by an education provider (Either college or university) after successful completion of studies is referred to as a degree. These degree courses mostly last to 3 to 4 years. Unlike a degree
column5: it can be awarded by a university only. It leads to specialization in a specific course. Your always have pathway to apply for higher studies like Bachelor or Associate Degree after completion of diploma level courses. Just a short walk away from the Fish Market in Pyrmont is this set of three sandstone blocks
column2: inscribed ""PARADISE."" This is a monument to one of the most famous sandstone quarries that existed in the Pyrmont area. The 'Paradise' quarry was known as such because of the relative ease of work there
column3: the location and the depth of the stone made for much less backbreaking work than quarries not far away.  Paradise was owned by Charles Saunders
column4: who employed a large number of Scottish quarrymen
column5: who gave the quarry the nickname in the 1850s.  The men who worked the stone were highly skilled and organised. Their trade union was the first in the world to win the eight-hour working day in 1855.  #sydney #history #travel #pyrmont #city #sandstone #quarry #paradise #work #union #heritage #oldsydney #fairwork #immigration #oldsydney #scotland #nsw #australia #ilovesydney #visitsydney #historicsydney

ğŸ’– GRATITUDE MONDAY ğŸ’–  It's a public holiday here today and I took some time while sitting at the laundromat (our washing machine and tv broke within a week of each otherğŸ™ˆ) to really focus on what I am grateful for and boy there is so much when you take some time to look for it! But 3 things really stood out for me... ğŸ’– This past weekend was the 5th anniversary of my mom's kidney transplant. The 4 people involved in this miraculous surgery made history by being South Africa's first ever Domino Transplant. The 2-donors and 2-recipients are all healthy and strong 5-years on
column2: what a massive blessing! ğŸ’– This weekend my mother in law went home from hospital after her surgery to remove some cancer tumours. We are hopeful for great results ğŸ™ğŸ¼ ğŸ’– Lastly I am super grateful to be able to ride our bikes in a state park with family and friends not having to worry about our safety.  Wishing you and your family a wonderful week wherever you are in the world ğŸŒ . . . #gratitude #gratitudemonday #theimmigrationlighthouse #expatlife #expatliving #emotionalwellbeing #community #coach #immigrationmentor #migrantcoach #positivethinking #migrationcoach #immigrant #immigration #kidneytransplant #cancersucks #bikerides #family #safety

column1: What is the â€œpublic chargeâ€ rule?  The public charge concept was first established by Congress in 1882 in order to allow the U.S. government to deny a U.S. visa to anyone who â€œis likely at any time to become a public chargeâ€ â€” but without defining what â€œpublic chargeâ€ means. Under today's administration
column2: the â€œPublic Charge ruleâ€ is being interpreted broadly to reduce the number of people who are eligible for green cards and other visas
column3: by redefining what makes them dependent on government benefits â€” or â€œlikelyâ€ to be in the future.  Click link on bio to watch the update from Atty. Carl Shusterman  #publicchargerule #immigrationattorney #immigrationmatters #immigrants #immigration

There are different types of permanent residences in the US
column2: there is the conditional permanent residence and the permanent legal residence. The difference is that one of them grants a 2-year permit and the other one grants 10 years. Besides the length
column3: the two-year conditional permanent residence cannot be renewed
column4: and the ten-year permanent legal residence can be renewed and you can obtain your citizenship before the permit expires.  Permanent Legal Residence If the case is that you qualified a green card for ten years
column5: you can apply for your American citizenship before it expires. Please note that after you have received your Permanent Legal Residence
column6: you must renew it before it expires.  If you need assistance

column1: I had the honor of playing a role in writing The Human Trafficking and Exploitation Prevention Training Act
column2: a bipartisan piece of legislation with Congressman Vern Buchanan and Congressman Alcee Hastings last year.  With this
column3: the Department of Justice released $750
column4: 000 to support victims of human trafficking. The Act also created a grant program within the Office of Trafficking in Persons
column5: under the Department of Health and Human Services
column6: to provide training for students
column7: teachers and other school personnel on the warning signs of human trafficking. The bill is endorsed by several human trafficking prevention groups. How doÂ the Government knows ifÂ immigrants are succeeding inÂ Canadaâ€™s economy? ğŸ¤”ğŸ˜‰ â € Two reasons why income isÂ aÂ misleading indicator ofÂ economic integration â € Focusing onÂ salaries can beÂ misleading for several reasons. ğŸ‘‰First
column2: immigrants tend toÂ arrive inÂ Canada atÂ aÂ disadvantage inÂ the labour market. They often arrive without social orÂ professional networks and need time for Canadian employers toÂ recognize their skills. Immigrants that earn high salaries typically need atÂ least five years inÂ Canada before their salaries match those ofÂ Canadian-born individuals. â € ğŸ‘‰The second reason why income can beÂ aÂ misleading indicator ofÂ economic integration isÂ that the majority ofÂ Canadaâ€™s immigrants are welcomed for social and humanitarian reasons. â € Immigrant economic integration isÂ better than you think â € ğŸ‘One ofÂ these metrics isÂ the degree toÂ which immigrants participate inÂ the housing market. The biggest purchase that Canadians and immigrants make isÂ buying aÂ home. The average value ofÂ anÂ immigrantâ€™s home inÂ Toronto and Vancouver isÂ the same asÂ that ofÂ the Canadian-born population. This tells usÂ that immigrants bring significant savings with them which increases their purchasing power inÂ Canada. â € ğŸ‘ŒSecond
column3: the household incomes ofÂ immigrants are nearly atÂ the same level asÂ those ofÂ Canadian households. The average immigrant household earns about $85
column4: 000 per year
column5: compared with about $90
column6: 000 for Canadian households. This tells usÂ that even ifÂ the average immigrant earner makes less money than the average Canadian. â € Immigrants are succeeding inÂ CanadağŸ˜Š â € There isÂ noÂ question that more can beÂ done toÂ improve the economic performance ofÂ immigrants inÂ Canada. AtÂ the same time
column7: there are numerous indicators that undoubtedly show immigrants are succeeding inÂ Canada. â € Canada will continue toÂ improve its economic class programs and make investments inÂ settlement and integration supports. This
column8: plus the fact that nine million Canadians will reach retirement age within the next decade suggests that the economic performance ofÂ immigrants
column9: asÂ well asÂ their incomes

column1: The film ""Nikkei"" is available at www.MOWIES.com in English or Japanese - Spanish Simultaneous!!!. ------- The documentary ""Nikkei"" by Kaori Flores Yonekura is a documentary about the japanese inmigration and the indentity of Latin American japanese diaspora. In Nikkei
column2: director Kaori Flores Yonekura tells the story of her grandparentsâ€™ intrepid journey from Japan to Peru to Venezuela. Along the way
column3: their personal search for a new home is set against the larger backdrop of the history of Japanese immigration to Latin America: from servitude in Peru
column4: to the anti-Japanese media campaigns in World War II
column5: to propaganda and promises of a better life in Venezuela. Nikkei is a fascinating and artfully constructed documentary that uses a personal testimony to reconstruct a subject of Latin American history.  Topics: #Immigration #Diaspora #Identity and culture #History #LatinAmericanStudies #AsianStudies #Politics #SpanishStudies #WorldWarII #WWII #ConcentrationCamps  The DVD and various licenses have been acquired by the Japanese American National Museum (JANM. column1: Last Thursday I (Naresh Gehi) met with Congressman Gregory Meeks. We had a wonderful conversation. Congressman Meeks is a wonderful man

column3: and especially in New York City. It was a pleasure to get to speak with him on the current-event issues regarding immigration.  Finally
column4: this Wednesday will be another edition of Green Card with Gehi. Green Card with Gehi will be here on facebook

column1: Today
column2: staff from the Young Center witnessed the first video-hearing (VTCs) for #immigrant children in government custody in the #Houston area. Here is what we saw. ğŸ‘‡ Most of these children were transported from government facilities to Houstonâ€™s #immigration court
column3: while others remained in programs located in Corpus Christi-but all of them were appearing before an immigration judge in Atlanta
column4: who had no in-person contact with the children. Children who had arrived at 8:00 amâ€”including a five-year-oldâ€”restlessly waited in Corpus Christi for hours today as the court struggled with technical difficulties. At a certain point
column5: the court was adjourned for more than an hour in an effort to resolve the technical issues. During the video hearings
column6: a series of technical difficulties caused confusion and frustration. At one point children unexpectedly overheard an unrelated hearing over the VTC system
column7: in which someone discussed a violent encounter and their fear of returning to their country. In addition to the technical difficulties that confuse the children and frustrate the judges
column8: video hearings prevent judges from observing childrenâ€™s body language or even making eye contact as they make life-altering decisions about immigrant children. One child who spoke an indigenous language was unable to understand two different interpreters. At the end of the hearing
column9: the child was told to prepare to move forward with his case next month
column10: with no guarantee an interpreter would be available at that time. Immigration court hearings are incredibly challenging for children in custody
column11: many of whom donâ€™t have attorneys or Child Advocates. They become unacceptably unfair when they take place by video. We join other childrenâ€™s rights organizations and allies and demand an immediate end to this practice.

column1: What a fuckin ride!  The ""Montreal Experiment"" as I called it technically came to an end last week.  In May 2018 I moved to Montreal because I felt a pull to the city and decided to listen to that feeling. My story is rooted in immigration
column2: and I felt I needed to move to the city where I was born which was also the city that my parents first immigrated to when they left Iran. Having grown up in Virginia
column3: Montreal always felt like a far off magical place that we only visited sometimes.  I moved with very vague ideas of what I wanted to do and what my time there would look like. I applied to graduate school there but didn't get in
column4: and still moved despite that because there was something telling me that I needed to be in that city.  In the end the adventure looked a million times different than I could've imagined in the best possible way. There were lots of ups and lots of downs but it was all worth the uncertainty.  I'm so thankful for everything I learned during these past two years and all the friendships I've made.  Not everything I tried worked out
column5: but I really credit my strength and fitness journey with giving me the tools necessary to keep pushing hard
column6: and become comfortable being uncomfortable. I also recommend jiu jitsu to anyone who moves to a new city on their own. It immediately gives you new goals to work towards within a really amazing community of people.  My biggest takeaway from the experience is that if you feel a pull towards something
column7: go. Keep an open mind and you'll figure out the rest along the way. .
